@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "REQUIREMENTS" "GPDial v1.0 - Requirements"
@NEXT "WHATISIT"
@PREV "DISCLAIMER"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}@{u}Requirements@{ub}@{uu}

  GPDial requires OS 2.04 or above. It will normally be used in
  conjunction with AmiTCP.

  I developed GPDial using

      @{b}o@{ub} CygnusEd Pro V3.5
      @{b}o@{ub} Lattice C v5.01
      @{b}o@{ub} GadToolsBox v2.0b
      @{b}o@{ub} DPaint 4 AGA
      @{b}o@{ub} BrushCon v1.20

  It was tested on an A1200 running

      @{b}o@{ub} WB 3.0
      @{b}o@{ub} AmiTCP v2.2 & 2.3
      @{b}o@{ub} rhslip.device

  Note: Although GPDial should run on OS 2.04 it has not been tested on
        such a machine. It has also not been tested with a ppp.device.

@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "WHATISIT" "GPDial v1.0 - What is it"
@NEXT "INSTALLATION"
@PREV "REQUIREMENTS"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}@{u}So What Is It?@{ub}@{uu}

  Well after several hours of installing AmiTCP and finally getting
  it to work I set about looking for a dialer. There are several dialers
  out there, but none of them met my needs. So GPDial was born.

  GPDial is a script based dialer that has a fancy GUI. It has the
  capability of storing several entries in its phone book. So if you
  have more than one service provider, it could be the dialer for you.

  GPDial doesn't necessarily have to be used with AmiTCP. It can be used
  to automate any sequence of events. Especially ones involving the serial
  port.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "INSTALLATION" "GPDial v1.0 - Installation"
@NEXT "USAGE"
@PREV "WHATISIT"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}@{u}Installation@{ub}@{uu}

  The installation is quite straight forward. There is an installation
  script that will do everything for you. To run it type

                     installer Install.GPDial

  or double click on its icon.

  The installation script will copy GPDial to a directory of your choice
  the default is AmiTCP:bin

  Replace will then be copied to a directory of your choice the default
  is C:. Replace is a find and replace utility. See its doc for more info.

  The config files are then copied. GPDial will look for the config file
  in the following places:

              The location held in environment variable GPD_CONFIG 
              AmiTCP:db/
              INet:db/
              S:

  The installation script will generate the GPD_CONFIG environment
  variable for you in ENV: and ENVARC:

  The next step involves copying 2 GPDial scripts into a directory of your
  choice.

  Finally the doc files are copied to a place of your choice. The GPDial
  doc (this file) has 4 iff pictures which will also be copied, it might
  be best if the guide and the iffs are placed in a directory of their
  own (it would certainly be neater). The Replace doc is also copied to
  a directory of your choice.

  and thats it.

@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "USAGE" "GPDial v1.0 - Using GPDial"
@NEXT "GUI"
@PREV "INSTALLATION"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}@{u}Using GPDial@{ub}@{uu}

  GPDial can be run from either the cli or workbench. It must be noted
  however that GPDial requires a stack of 10000 bytes. This is handled
  by its icon if run from workbench. If you run it from the cli remember
  and change the stack with the command:

              stack 10000

  I use GPDial from a menu using "tools daemon". This supports different
  stack sizes.

  If GPDial is run from the workbench a window will open.
  see the @{"User Interface" LINK "GUI"} section for more details.

  GPdial has a few command line arguments. They are:

        @{fg shine}GPDial [-options] [script | phonebook entry]

              options
                 n         No startup script
                 c         Don't open serial port on startup
                 e         Run script associated with the phonebook entry

               script      Name of a script to run@{fg text}


  Normally no arguments are required.

  If a script is given then the user interface is not displayed.

  GPDial normally opens the serial port as soon as it starts. This can
  be avoided by using the 'c' flag. (the serial port can be opened latter
  on with the @{"SETSER" LINK "S_SETSER"} script command).

  After GPDial has allocated all resources it will attempt to run the
  startup script (if there is one). To stop this happening use the 'n'
  flag.

  If the 'e' flag is given then the script associated with the phonebook
  entry is executed. There are several benefits of doing this.

  When a script is executed from the @{"User Interface" LINK "GUI"} several special
  variables are filled in. See @{"GPDial Variables" LINK "VARIABLES"} section for more
  details. If a script is executed from the command line a few of these
  variables a not filled in. This is overcome by using the 'e' flag. It
  pretends the script has been executed from the interface.

  It should be noted that when using the 'e' flag you also enter the
  phonebook entry name to execute, NOT a script name.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "GUI" "GPDial v1.0 - User Interface"
@NEXT "SCRIPTS"
@PREV "USAGE"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}@{u}The User Interface@{ub}@{uu}

  When GPDial starts the @{"Main window" LINK main.iff/main} is displayed.

  The @{"Config window" LINK config.iff/main} is used to edit certain details and the name
  of the startup script.

  To add or edit a Phonebook entry the @{"Phonebook edit window" LINK Entry.iff/main} is used.

  When a script runs the @{"SHOW" LINK "S_SHOW"} command will display the @{"Progress window" LINK Progress.iff/main}.

  The close gadget on the progress window will not terminate the script.
  It does exactly the same as the @{"HIDE" LINK "S_HIDE"} command.

  If the abort gadget is clicked the script will terminate. If however
  the gadget is clicked while the modem is dialing or connected the
  connection will continue to exist. Abort merely terminates the script.

@ENDNODE  

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "SCRIPTS" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts"
@NEXT "VARIABLES"
@PREV "GUI"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}@{u}GPDial Scripts@{ub}@{uu}

Here is a list of all the scripting commands

     @{"ACCEPT     " LINK "S_ACCEPT"}      - Get input from the user
     @{"CLOSE      " LINK "S_CLOSE"}      - Close the serial port
     @{"END        " LINK "S_END"}      - End of the script
     @{"EXECUTE    " LINK "S_EXECUTE"}      - Execute a command
     @{"EXTRACT    " LINK "S_EXTRACT"}      - Extract a word from a string
     @{"GOTO       " LINK "S_GOTO"}      - Goto a Label
     @{"HIDE       " LINK "S_HIDE"}      - Hide the @{"progress window" LINK Progress.iff/main}
     @{"IF         " LINK "S_IF"}      - Selection
     @{"MATH       " LINK "S_MATH"}      - Do a calculation
     @{"PAUSE      " LINK "S_PAUSE"}      - Pause for a length of time
     @{"PRINT      " LINK "S_PRINT"}      - Print a message to the progress window
     @{"PRINTERROR " LINK "S_PRINTERROR"}      - Display an error message
     @{"QUIT       " LINK "S_QUIT"}      - Quit the script
     @{"REMCHAR    " LINK "S_REMCHAR"}      - Remove a character from a string
     @{"REMOVE     " LINK "S_REMOVE"}      - Remove the progress window
     @{"SEND       " LINK "S_SEND"}      - Send a string to the serial port
     @{"SET        " LINK "S_SET"}      - Set a variable
     @{"SETSER     " LINK "S_SETSER"}      - Change the serial port settings
     @{"SHOW       " LINK "S_SHOW"}      - Show the progress window
     @{"WAIT       " LINK "S_WAIT"}      - Wait for a string from the serial port

  @{b}Special Control Characters@{ub}
  Several characters can not be displayed normally. In order to display
  them or send them to the serial port you should use the control
  character sequence. They are as follows:

    \n - Carriage return
    \r - Newline
    \f - Formfeed
    \" - The quote char "
    \$ - The dollar char $
    \\ - The slash char \

  An extra control char is also available to the @{"SEND" LINK "S_SEND"} command:

    \w - wait for 1 second.

  Remember to end all commands to the modem with a \r.
  
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_ACCEPT" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Accept"
@NEXT "S_CLOSE"
@PREV "SCRIPTS"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}ACCEPT <string> [HIDE] [BLANK] [label]@{ub}

  This command will prompt the user for input.

  The result is placed in a variable called @{"GPD_INPUT" LINK "VARIABLES"}.

  If the "HIDE" option is given then the text entered will be hidden
  (ideal for passwords). The label will be jumped to if "Cancel" is
  clicked, if it is omitted then the script will continue as if "Ok"
  was clicked.

  Not entering a string in the requester will simulate clicking
  "Cancel" unless the "BLANK" option is activated.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_CLOSE" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Close"
@NEXT "S_END"
@PREV "S_ACCEPT"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}CLOSE@{ub}

  This command will force the release of the serial port.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_END" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - End"
@NEXT "S_EXECUTE"
@PREV "S_CLOSE"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}END@{ub}

  The end of a script.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_EXECUTE" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Execute"
@NEXT "S_EXTRACT"
@PREV "S_END"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}EXECUTE <command> [label]@{ub}

  Execute an AmigaDOS command, if the command fails the label will be
  jumped to.

  It should be noted that only system errors will cause control to
  jump to the label. If actual command returns an error code
  it will be ignored.

  Any other output from the command will also be ignored.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_EXTRACT" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Extract"
@NEXT "S_GOTO"
@PREV "S_EXECUTE"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}EXTRACT <string> <position> [label]@{ub}

  This command will take the word at <position> in the <string> and
  place it in a variable called @{"GPD_VALUE" LINK "VARIABLES"}.

  The label will be jumped to if there are not enough words in the string
  for the operation.
  e.g.

  EXTRACT "your IP address is 146.176.164.13" 5
  PRINT $GPD_VALUE

  gives:

  146.176.164.13
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_GOTO" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Goto"
@NEXT "S_HIDE"
@PREV "S_EXTRACT"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}GOTO <label>@{ub}

  Jump to a label. Labels are denoted with the @{"LAB",LINK "S_LAB"} command.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_HIDE" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Hide"
@NEXT "S_IF"
@PREV "S_GOTO"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}HIDE@{ub}

  This command will hide the @{"progress window" LINK Progress.iff/main}.

  It can be redisplayed with a @{"SHOW" LINK "S_SHOW"} command.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_IF" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - if/else/endif"
@NEXT "S_LAB"
@PREV "S_HIDE"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}IF <operand1 operator operand2>
..
ELSE
..
ENDIF@{ub}

  Checks to see if the two operands match.

  Valid operators are:

  =   Check for equality        - Strings and Numerics.
  >   Greater than              - Numerics only.
  <   Less than                 - Numerics only.
  >=  Greater than or equal to  - Numerics only.
  <=  Less than or equal to     - Numerics only.
  !=  not equal to              - Strings and Numerics.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_LAB" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Lab"
@NEXT "S_MATH"
@PREV "S_IF"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}LAB <label:>@{ub}

  This command is normally just skipped over. Other commands
  use it to allow control to jump to different parts of the script.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_MATH" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Math"
@NEXT "S_PAUSE"
@PREV "S_LAB"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}MATH <variable> <=> <operand1> <operation> <operand2>@{ub}

  This command allows you to do simple maths.

  Operations are:
  +   Plus
  -   Subtract
  *   Multiply
  \   Divide

  e.g.
  SET SUM TO 1
  MATH SUM = $SUM + 1
  PRINT $SUM

  gives:
  2
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_PAUSE" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Pause"
@NEXT "S_PRINT"
@PREV "S_MATH"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}PAUSE <time>@{ub}

  This command will pause the script for the stated number of seconds.
  The <time> must be numeric and greater than 0.

  A PAUSE length of less than or equal to 0 is invalid.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_PRINT" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Print"
@NEXT "S_PRINTERROR"
@PREV "S_PAUSE"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}PRINT <string>@{ub}

  This command displays a string in the @{"progress window" LINK Progress.iff/main}.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_PRINTERROR" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Printerror"
@NEXT "S_QUIT"
@PREV "S_PRINT"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}PRINTERROR <string>@{ub}

  This command display the string as an error message.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_QUIT" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Quit"
@NEXT "S_REMCHAR"
@PREV "S_PRINTERROR"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}QUIT@{ub}

  This command will quit GPDial.
  If the script was run from the GUI it will also be ended.

  This command could be used on successful connection to your service
  provider.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_REMCHAR" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Remchar"
@NEXT "S_REMOVE"
@PREV "S_QUIT"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}REMCHAR <string> <value>@{ub}

  This command will remove the char at the given position and will
  shuffle the rest of the chars down.
  If you want to remove the last char of the string and you don't know
  its length you can use a value of -1.

  The resultant string is placed in the variable @{"GPD_TEXT" LINK "VARIABLES"}

  e.g.

  SET test to "hello there"
  REMCHAR $test 6
  PRINT $test

  gives:

  hellothere
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_REMOVE" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Remove"
@NEXT "S_SEND"
@PREV "S_REMCHAR"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}REMOVE [time]@{ub}

  This command removes (closes) the @{"progress window" LINK Progress.iff/main} after "time" seconds has
  expired. It is removed immediately if the time is not stated.

  The time value must be greater than 0.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_SEND" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Send"
@NEXT "S_SET"
@PREV "S_REMOVE"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}SEND <string> [HIDE]@{ub}

  This command will sends a string to the modem.
  A message is displayed in the @{"progress window" LINK Progress.iff/main} everytime a SEND is
  executed. The HIDE flag can be used to stop this. It is ideal for
  passwords.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_SET" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Set"
@NEXT "S_SETSER"
@PREV "S_SEND"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}SET <variable> <TO> <string>@{ub}

  This command will set a variable to a string. Numeric variables are
  also treated in this way

  e.g.

  SET text TO "Hello"
  SET value1 TO "1"
  SET result TO "0"
  MATH result = $value1 + "3"
  PRINT $text
  PRINT $result	

  gives:

  Hello
  4
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_SETSER" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Setser"
@NEXT "S_SHOW"
@PREV "S_SET"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}SETSER <baud> <data> <stop> <parity>@{ub}

  This command will open the serial port if it is closed.
  It will also change the serial port settings.

  baud   -      300
                600
               1200
               2400
               4800
               9600
              19200
              38400
              57600
              76800
             115200

  data   - 7    7 data bits.
           8    8 data bits.

  stop   - 1    1 stop bit.
           2    2 stop bits.

  Parity - N    No parity.
           O    Odd parity
           E    Even parity.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_SHOW" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Show"
@NEXT "S_WAIT"
@PREV "S_SETSER"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}SHOW [ABORT] [ALL]@{ub}

  This command shows the progress of the connection in a @{"progress window" LINK Progress.iff/main},
  the options are:

     ABORT - This gives an abort button to abort the script. Care should
             be taken with the abort feature. If it is clicked while the
             modem is dialing or connected the connection will continue
             to exist. Abort merely terminates the script.

     ALL   - This shows ALL output. Normally only @{"PRINT" LINK "S_PRINT"} statements and
             the odd system message will be displayed in the progress
             window. If ALL is stated then characters received from the
             modem during a @{"WAIT" LINK "S_WAIT"} or @{"WAITLINE" LINK "S_WAIT"} are also displayed.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "S_WAIT" "GPDial v1.0 - Scripts - Wait"
@NEXT "VARIABLES"
@PREV "S_SHOW"
@TOC "SCRIPTS"

@{b}WAIT <"string"> [OR <"string"> ..] [timeout <label>]@{ub}   (max of 4 strings)

  This command will waits for a string to be received from the serial port.
  The string received is placed a variable called @{"GPD_STRING" LINK "VARIABLES"}, and the
  whole line with the string in is placed in a variable called @{"GPD_LINE" LINK "VARIABLES"}.

  There is a maximum of 4 strings that can be waited for. They are
  separated with the "OR" statement.

  An optional timeout is available. If this time limit runs out before
  the string is received control jumps to the label.

  WAIT will wait for a string to be received and then continue with the
  script. If however you wish to wait for a whole line (256 chars or
  newline terminated) then WAITLINE should be used in place of WAIT.

  e.g.

  WAIT "CONNECT" OR "BUSY" OR "ENGAGED" 30 Error

  or

  WAITLINE "your IP address is" 10 Error
@ENDNODE  

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "VARIABLES" "GPDial v1.0 - Variables"
@NEXT "ERROR"
@PREV "SCRIPTS"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}@{u}GPDial Variables@{ub}@{uu}

This is a list of variables that GPDial knows about. More variables can be
added by scripts. These are deleted automatically when the script ends.

@{u}Variable name   Description                         Default value        @{uu}
GPD_BAUD        Holds the current Baud rate

GPD_DATA        Holds the current number of data
                bits

GPD_STOP        Holds the current number of stop
                bits

GPD_PARITY      Holds the current parity used

GPD_INIT        Holds the initialisation string     "AT\r"

GPD_DTROFF      Holds the string to ignore DTR     "AT&D0\r"

GPD_BUSY        Holds the busy string               "BUSY"

GPD_CONNECTED   Holds the connected string          "CONNECT"

GPD_HANGUP      Holds the hangup string             "\w\w+++\w\wATH\r"

GPD_PREDIAL     Holds the dial prefix               "ATDT"

GPD_SUFDIAL     Holds the dial sufix                "\r"

GPD_PHONENUMBER Holds the number of the site that
                is being called.

GPD_SITE        Holds the name of the site that
                is being called. If you don't
                run the script from the GUI than
                this variable will be blank.

GPD_LINE        This variable is filled after every
                WAIT or WAITLINE command succeeds.
                It holds the whole line that the
                command succeeded on.

GPD_USERNAME    This is the username for the system
                you are calling. It is filled in
                from the phonebook. If you don't
                run the script from the GUI than
                this variable will be blank.

GPD_PASSWORD    This is the password for the system
                you are calling. It is filled in
                from the phonebook. If you don't
                run the script from the GUI than
                this variable will be blank.

GPD_STRING      This variable is filled after every
                WAIT or WAITLINE command succeeds.
                It holds the actual string that the
                command succeeded on.

GPD_VALUE       This variable is filled after every
                EXTRACT command succeeds

GPD_TEXT        This variable is filled in by
                the REMCHAR command.

GPD_INPUT       This variable will be filled with
                the results of an ACCEPT.

GPD_AUTHOR      The name of the author of GPDial    "Adam Wasiak"

GPD_NAME        The name of the program             "GPDial"

GPD_VER         The version information for GPDial  "V1.0 ©1996 GhostSoft"

GPD_REG         Holds the registration details      "<unregistered>"
@ENDNODE  

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "ERROR" "GPDial v1.0 - Script Errors"
@NEXT "REGISTER"
@PREV "VARIABLES"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}@{u}Script Errors@{ub}@{uu}

  This is a list of error messages that can be produced by incorrect
  scripts.

@{b}Invalid command@{ub}
  You have tried to use a command that GPDial does not understand.
  It is probably just a spelling mistake (I make them all the time).

@{b}Missing LAB:@{ub}
  You tried to do a @{"GOTO" LINK "S_GOTO"} to a label that does not exist. This error
  can be produced by @{"GOTO" LINK "S_GOTO"} @{"ACCEPT" LINK "S_ACCEPT"} @{"WAIT" LINK "S_WAIT"} or @{"WAITLINE" LINK "S_WAIT"}.

@{b}PAUSE length incorrect@{ub}
  You entered a @{"PAUSE" LINK "S_PAUSE"} length that wasn't numeric or was 0.

@{b}REMCHAR statement incorrect@{ub}
  The value part of the @{"REMCHAR" LINK "S_REMCHAR"} command is incorrect. It must be
  either -1 or greater than 0.

@{b}Invalid operator@{ub}
  The operator part of the @{"IF" LINK "S_IF"} statement is incorrect.
  Valid operators are: = != < > <= >=

@{b}Out of memory for SET statement@{ub}
  Your machine ran out of memory while trying to @{"SET" LINK "S_SET"} a variable.

@{b}SET statement incorrect@{ub}
  One of the @{"SET" LINK "S_SET"} statements is incorrect.

@{b}MATH statement incorrect@{ub}
  One of the @{"MATH" LINK "S_MATH"} statements is incorrect.

@{b}EXECUTE statement incorrect@{ub}
  One of the @{"EXECUTE" LINK "S_EXECUTE"} statements is incorrect.

@{b}EXTRACT statement incorrect@{ub}
  One of the @{"EXTRACT" LINK "S_EXTRACT"} statements is incorrect.

@{b}GOTO statement incorrect@{ub}
  One of the @{"GOTO" LINK "S_GOTO"} statements is incorrect.

@{b}IF statement incorrect@{ub}
  One of the @{"IF" LINK "S_IF"} statements is incorrect.

@{b}LAB statement incorrect@{ub}
  One of the @{"LAB" LINK "S_LAB"} statements is incorrect.

@{b}PRINT statement incorrect@{ub}
  One of the @{"PRINT" LINK "S_PRINT"} statements is incorrect.

@{b}PRINTERROR statement incorrect@{ub}
  One of the @{"PRINTERROR" LINK "S_PRINTERROR"} statements is incorrect.

@{b}SEND statement incorrect@{ub}
  One of the @{"SEND" LINK "S_SEND"} statements is incorrect.

@{b}MATH attempted a divide by 0@{ub}
  A @{"MATH" LINK "S_MATH"} statement attempted to divide by 0

@{b}MATH variable not declared@{ub}
  Attempted to assign a value to an undeclared variable in a @{"MATH" LINK "S_MATH"}
  statement.

@{b}ACCEPT must have a string@{ub}
  An @{"ACCEPT" LINK "S_ACCEPT"} statement was encounter that did not have a <string>.

@{b}Timeout length incorrect@{ub}
  @{"WAIT" LINK "S_WAIT"} or @{"WAITLINE" LINK "S_WAIT"} timeout length that wasn't numeric or was 0.

@{b}<baud> in SETSER is incorrect@{ub}
  The baud rate part of the @{"SETSER" LINK "S_SETSER"} command should be:
       300
       600
      1200
      2400
      4800
      9600
     19200
     38400
     57600
     76800
    115200

@{b}<data> in SETSER is incorrect@{ub}
  The data part of the @{"SETSER" LINK "S_SETSER"} command should be
      7    7 data bits.
      8    8 data bits.

@{b}<stop> in SETSER is incorrect@{ub}
  The stop part of the @{"SETSER" LINK "S_SETSER"} command should be
      1    1 stop bit.
      2    2 stop bits.

@{b}<parity> in SETSER is incorrect@{ub}
  The parity part of the @{"SETSER" LINK "S_SETSER"} command should be
      N    No parity.
      O    Odd parity.
      E    Even parity.

@{b}Serial device closed@{ub}
  This error occurs when you try to perform an operation on the
  serial device when it is closed. It is produced by
      @{"SEND    " LINK "S_SEND"}
      @{"WAIT    " LINK "S_WAIT"}
      @{"WAITLINE" LINK "S_WAIT"}

  NOTE: @{"SETSER" LINK "S_SETSER"} will reopen the serial device if it is closed.

@{b}Can't write to serial port@{ub}
  A @{"SEND" LINK "S_SEND"} command failed for some unknown reason.

@{b}Can't reopen serial device@{ub}
  One of the @{"SETSER" LINK "S_SETSER"} statements has failed to reopen the closed serial port.

@{b}SETSER can't change settings@{ub}
  A @{"SETSER" LINK "S_SETSER"} command failed to change the serial port settings.

@{b}Can't open progress window@{ub}
  One of the @{"SHOW" LINK "S_SHOW"} failed to open the progress window.

@{b}Too many "OR"s@{ub}
  One of the @{"WAIT" LINK "S_WAIT"} or @{"WAITLINE" LINK "S_WAIT"} statements has too many ORs.
@ENDNODE

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "REGISTER" "GPDial v1.0 - Registration"
@NEXT "BUGS"
@PREV "ERROR"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}@{u}Registration@{ub}@{uu}

  This version of GPDial is absolutely free. See @{"disclaimer" LINK "DISCLAIMER"} for more info.

  I am currently working on a new version of GPDial. This will be
  registration only and available early in April 1996.

  The new version will have the following features:

  @{b}o@{ub} Multiple phone numbers per site. (for sites with multiple lines
                                      each with different numbers).
  @{b}o@{ub} Arexx port.
  @{b}o@{ub} More scripting commands.
      @{b}o@{ub} Logfiles.
      @{b}o@{ub} Loops.
      @{b}o@{ub} Ask (YES/NO) requester.
  @{b}o@{ub} Variable progress window size.
  @{b}o@{ub} Enhanced abort processing.
  @{b}o@{ub} Option to use a device other than the serial.device.
  @{b}o@{ub} Hotkey which will bring up the progress window.
  @{b}o@{ub} Encrypted and hidden passwords.
  @{b}o@{ub} Password protection.
  @{b}o@{ub} Any other ideas that are mailed to me.

  To register you should send 10 pounds sterling to @{"me" LINK "CONTACT"}.
  If you don't have EMail you should also send a S.A.E. big enough to
  hold a disk. In return I will send you a key file. You will also need
  to download GPDial1.1_reg.lha.

  To register all I will need to know is your name and address. If
  you have an EMail address you should also send that too. If you are
  registering on behalf of a company you should also send the company
  name.

  @{b}NOTE:@{ub} v1.1 is still under development and will be released in early
        April 1996. Any registration fees I receive before then will be
        held untill it is released.
@ENDNODE  

@REM ****************************************************************

@NODE "BUGS" "GPDial v1.0 - Things you should know about"
@NEXT "CONTACT"
@PREV "REGISTER"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}@{u}Things You Should Know About@{ub}@{uu}

  Here are a few things to watch out for.

@{b}1.@{ub}
  Control chars (\n \r \\ \" and \$) that occur within the @{"GPD_INPUT" LINK "VARIABLES"}
  variable will not be evaluated. This can only happen with the @{"ACCEPT" LINK "S_ACCEPT"}
  command.
  e.g.

  ACCEPT "Enter a string"      ; you entry "Yes\\No"
  PRINT $GPD_INPUT

  gives    Yes\\No
  and not  Yes\No


@{b}2.@{ub}
  Remember commands that go to the modem must end in \r.
  e.g.

  SEND "AT\r"

@{b}3.@{ub}
  The stack must be greater than 4096 - Recommended value is 10000.

@{b}4.@{ub}
  When running scripts from the command line it should be noted that
  several variables are not filled in. Namely:

  GPD_SITE
  GPD_PHONENUMBER
  GPD_USERNAME
  GPD_PASSWORD

  If the '-e' option is given the name given is searched for in the
  phonebook and the relevant details are filled in.

@{b}5.@{ub}
  Scripts will run with a closed serial port until a @{"WAIT" LINK "S_WAIT"} or @{"SEND" LINK "S_SEND"} command.

  If you attempt to run a script and the serial port is closed (either by
  the -c command line arg or the CLOSE command) the serial port settings
  for the script (Baud rate, Data bits, Stop bits and Parity) will
  not be set. However it can be opened latter on with the following
  command:

    SETSER $GPD_BAUD $GPD_DATA $GPD_STOP $GPD_PARITY

@{b}5.@{ub}
  During testing I noticed something strange. Five modem settings don't
  seem to work. I understand that the serial.device can't handle
  certain settings. Here are the settings that don't work:

     8/1/O
     8/1/E
     8/2/O
     8/2/E
     7/1/N

  I'm not sure if these are the settings that are meant to not work
  or if there is a bug in the code. If someone knows please mail me.
@ENDNODE  

